4. The eyes.

As in most of the Hyperiidean families they eyes are also strongly developed in the Oxycephalids‚ and consist of a great number of ocelli. These ocelli are not separated into an Upper-eye, (Scheitel-Auge, Olaus), and two lateral portions on each side as in Thyropus and other genera, but in all the genera of the family Oxycephalidae‚ with the exception of Streetsia and Calamorhynchus‚ the ocelli are distribut-ed into two lateral portioris separated from one another at the crown of the head by a more or less narrow space.
